<TITLE> Nemtsov says he won't run for Russian presidency </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Moscow, Dec 26 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Veteran liberal politician Boris Nemtsov withdrew from Russia's presidential race on Wednesday, saying the opposition needed to put forward a single candidate in the March election. In a statement on his personal Web site , the former deputy prime minister and Union of Right Forces (SPS) presidential candidate said the Kremlin had turned democratic elections into "a clear-cut farce". "(The Kremlin) is using Goebbels-esque propaganda, law-enforcement and administrative resources against opposition candidates," Nemtsov said, referring to Nazi propaganda chief Joseph Goebbels. "The democratic opposition needs a single candidate. Therefore, I have made the decision to withdraw from participation in the presidential election." Nemtsov, nominated by the SPS on Dec 17, had little chance of beating Vladimir Putin's chosen candidate Dmitry Medvedev, as polls show most Russians will back whomever the highly-popular president backs. The SPS, which advocates free-market economics and political liberalism, scored well in the 1999 parliamentary election soon after its creation. But with Putin's rise to power months later, the party went into decline. It won no seats in a parliamentary election at the beginning of December, scoring less than one percent of the vote
